{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "National Grid Integration",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between generation methods and the high-voltage transmission network.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "We have established that electricity begins at a generation source—ranging from traditional fossil fuels like gas to renewables like wind or photovoltaic cells. To move this energy from these often remote locations to the rest of the country, it must enter the transmission 'super-highway'. This stage is strictly defined by specific high-voltage levels that allow for efficient, bulk transport of power before it ever reaches the local distribution networks."
    ],
    "questionText": "A new large-scale nuclear power station is being commissioned to provide bulk electricity to the national grid. Explain which specific voltage levels this station will use to transmit its power across the country and justify why these high-voltage levels (measured in kV) are used for this 'super-highway' stage instead of standard domestic voltages.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The response must identify the three UK transmission voltages: 400 kV, 275 kV, and 132 kV.",
      "The response must explain that high voltage is used to reduce energy loss (wasted as heat) over long distances.",
      "The response should demonstrate an understanding that 'kV' represents Kilovolts (thousands of volts), providing the necessary 'pressure' for bulk transmission.",
      "The response must distinguish these transmission levels from lower distribution or domestic voltages."
    ],
    "hint": "Recall the '132, 275, 400' rule and think about why we use high pressure (voltage) to move energy over hundreds of miles."
  }
}

